body:
This PR is not intended to be merged. I am opening it to continue discussion started in #2446

It contains my experiments with some ideas on how processes could be implemented.
This is far from ready so don't try to run it.
Please share any comments on the general approach and ignore the hacky details and the fact that this doesn't work yet - it can and will be cleaned up at a later stage once the approach is discussed and accepted and the code is actually working.

What I am doing here assumes verilator is executed with the `--output-split-cfuncs 1` flag (this will be important if we want block to be truly asynchronous).
My intention is to split all block to separate C functions to be able to run them in threads.
Instead of executing the Cfuncs in sequence I want to trigger next loop evaluation of a given process (achieved here with `std::condition_variable`).

Let me paste some of the generated code as a reference for the discussion.

For this simple verilog code:
```verilog
module t (/*AUTOARG*/
   // Inputs
   clk
   );
   input clk;

   initial begin
      $write("Simple first\n");
   end

   initial begin
      $write("Simple second\n");
      $write("*-* All Finished *-*\n");
      $finish;
   end

   always @ (posedge clk) begin
      $write("clk event");
   end
endmodule
```

At the moment, Verilator generates the following code (assuming the switch mentioned above is used):

```C++
void Vt_simple_two::_initial__TOP__1(Vt_simple_two__Syms* __restrict vlSymsp) {
    VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+    Vt_simple_two::_initial__TOP__1\n"); );
    Vt_simple_two* const __restrict vlTOPp VL_ATTR_UNUSED = vlSymsp->TOPp;
    // Body
    VL_WRITEF("Simple first\n");
}

void Vt_simple_two::_initial__TOP__2(Vt_simple_two__Syms* __restrict vlSymsp) {
    VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+    Vt_simple_two::_initial__TOP__2\n"); );
    Vt_simple_two* const __restrict vlTOPp VL_ATTR_UNUSED = vlSymsp->TOPp;
    // Body
    VL_WRITEF("Simple second\n*-* All Finished *-*\n");
    VL_FINISH_MT("test_regress/t/t_simple_two.v", 14, "");
}

void Vt_simple_two::_eval_initial(Vt_simple_two__Syms* __restrict vlSymsp) {
    VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+    Vt_simple_two::_eval_initial\n"); );
    Vt_simple_two* const __restrict vlTOPp VL_ATTR_UNUSED = vlSymsp->TOPp;
    // Body
    vlTOPp->_initial__TOP__1(vlSymsp);
    vlTOPp->_initial__TOP__2(vlSymsp);
    vlTOPp->__Vclklast__TOP__clk = vlTOPp->clk;
}
```

With the modifications from this PR we generate:
```C++
std::condition_variable _initial__TOP__1__cv;
std::mutex _initial__TOP__1__mtx;
bool _initial__TOP__1__ready = false;
void Vt_simple_two::_initial__TOP__1(Vt_simple_two__Syms* __restrict vlSymsp) {
    std::unique_lock<std::mutex> lck(_initial__TOP__1__mtx);
    do {
        while(!_initial__TOP__1__ready) {
            _initial__TOP__1__cv.wait(lck);
        }
        VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+    Vt_simple_two::_initial__TOP__1\n"); );
        Vt_simple_two* const __restrict vlTOPp VL_ATTR_UNUSED = vlSymsp->TOPp;
        // Body
        VL_WRITEF("Simple first\n");
        _initial__TOP__1__ready = false;
    } while (0 /* FIXME change to !finished for timed blocks */);
}

std::condition_variable _initial__TOP__2__cv;
std::mutex _initial__TOP__2__mtx;
bool _initial__TOP__2__ready = false;
void Vt_simple_two::_initial__TOP__2(Vt_simple_two__Syms* __restrict vlSymsp) {
    std::unique_lock<std::mutex> lck(_initial__TOP__2__mtx);
    do {
        while(!_initial__TOP__2__ready) {
            _initial__TOP__2__cv.wait(lck);
        }
        VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+    Vt_simple_two::_initial__TOP__2\n"); );
        Vt_simple_two* const __restrict vlTOPp VL_ATTR_UNUSED = vlSymsp->TOPp;
        // Body
        VL_WRITEF("Simple second\n*-* All Finished *-*\n");
        VL_FINISH_MT("test_regress/t/t_simple_two.v", 14, "");
        _initial__TOP__2__ready = false;
    } while (0 /* FIXME change to !finished for timed blocks */);
}

void Vt_simple_two::_eval_initial(Vt_simple_two__Syms* __restrict vlSymsp) {
    VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+    Vt_simple_two::_eval_initial\n"); );
    Vt_simple_two* const __restrict vlTOPp VL_ATTR_UNUSED = vlSymsp->TOPp;
    // Body
    _initial__TOP__1__ready = true;
    _initial__TOP__1__cv.notify_all();
    _initial__TOP__2__ready = true;
    _initial__TOP__2__cv.notify_all();
    vlTOPp->__Vclklast__TOP__clk = vlTOPp->clk;
}
```

Note that the threads are not even started yet but we can start the threads for `_initial__TOP__1`  etc (as they are already separate functions).

Advantages of this approach:
* delays can be handled easily with additional locks/condition_variables with some external time manager keeping track of which process is waiting for which time slot
* fork/join (all types) could be implemented the same way, all join types should work with this approach
* calling events and reacting to everything should be doable with this approach too

I am going to continue working on this to at least get a working proof of concept, but I am opening this PR already to allow you to share your thoughts early.

CC @wsnyder @martin-lueker
